# Model Cost Optimizer

When generating or executing a build plan, assign a specific Cursor model
to each phase/task. Default to the cheapest model that can reliably handle
the task's complexity. Escalate only when justified.

## Task-to-Model Mapping

| Task Complexity | Recommended Model | Escalate To |
|----------------|-------------------|-------------|
| Config files, .env, boilerplate, scaffolding | Gemini 2.5 Flash or Composer 2 | GPT-5.4 mini |
| Single-file CRUD routes, simple middleware | GPT-5.4 mini or Claude 4.5 Haiku | Claude 4.6 Sonnet |
| Multi-file components with interactions | Claude 4.6 Sonnet or GPT-5.4 | Claude 4.6 Opus |
| Complex aggregation, analytics, pipelines | GPT-5.4 or Claude 4.6 Sonnet | Claude 4.6 Opus |
| Test suites (well-specified) | GPT-5.4 mini | Claude 4.6 Sonnet |
| Full-page integration (many deps) | Claude 4.6 Sonnet | Claude 4.6 Opus |
| Architecture review, quality gates | Claude 4.6 Opus | -- |
| CSS/theme/styling only | Gemini 2.5 Flash | Composer 2 |

## Protocol

1. Before each plan phase, run `npm run cost-analyze` (if available)
   to get token estimates and model recommendations.
2. State the chosen model and estimated cost in the plan phase header.
3. If a phase fails or produces poor output, escalate one tier and note
   the reason.
4. Never use Opus Fast ($30/$150) unless the user explicitly requests it.
5. Prefer Auto mode for exploratory/ambiguous tasks where routing helps.

## Escalation Triggers

Escalate to a more expensive model when:
- The task requires reasoning across >50K tokens of context
- Previous attempt with cheaper model produced incorrect output
- The task involves security-sensitive logic (auth, input validation)
- The task requires coordinating >5 files simultaneously

## Cost Tracking

Include a cost estimate line in each plan phase:
`Model: [name] | Est. input: ~[X]K tokens | Est. output: ~[Y]K tokens | Est. cost: ~$[Z]`
